3 and
4 (f) reasonable attorney fees and costs incurred in bringing the action.
5 (2) In addition to the remedies provided in subsection (1), a victim may seek restitution.
6 (3) For each unique violation under [section 2], a plaintiff's recovery of statutory damages is limited
7 to one subsection under subsection (1)(e)(i) through (1)(e)(iii).
8 (4) In an action in which the remedies under subsection (1) are ordered:
9 (a) compensatory damages for each violation must be paid to the victim;
10 (b) the amount of punitive and statutory damages must be apportioned for each violation as
11 follows:
12 (i) 50% to a victim, or equally divided among multiple victims, if reasonably identified by the court
13 regardless of the victim's involvement as a plaintiff;
14 (ii) 30% to a private plaintiff or, if there is no private plaintiff, to a victim, or equally divided among
15 multiple victims, if reasonably identified by the court regardless of the victim's involvement as a plaintiff;
16 (iii) the remaining amount to the department to be deposited into a state special revenue account
17 to the credit of the department; and
18 (c) attorney fees and costs shall be paid to the party who incurred the fees and costs.
19
20 NEW SECTION. Section 5. Codification instruction. [Sections 1 through 4] are intended to be
21 codified as a new part of a new chapter of Title 30, and the provisions of Title 30 apply to [sections 1 through 4].
22
23 NEW SECTION. Section 6. Severability. If a part of [this act] is invalid, all valid parts that are
24 severable from the invalid part remain in effect. If a part of [this act] is invalid in one or more of its applications,
25 the part remains in effect in all valid applications that are severable from the invalid applications.
